Documentation.name: LieberLieber SYSMOD
Documentation.notes: SYSMOD-v4.2 profile defined by Tim Weilkiens https://mbse4u.com/sysmod/ (OMG SysML1.4-5) Developed by Roman Bretz (lieberlieber.com), Horst Kargl (sparxsystems.eu), Bob Hruska (sparxservices.eu), Franz Müller (sparxsystems.eu) and Philipp Kalenda (lieberlieber.com).

Stereotype.name: Actuator
Stereotype.notes: External system that has an effect on the environment and is controlled by the system of interest.

Stereotype.name: BoundarySystem
Stereotype.notes: External system that is an interface between another external system and the system of interest.

Stereotype.name: Conjugated
Stereotype.notes: Stereotype is applied to a generalization relationship that has the same effect than the isConjugated property of a SysML Port. The direction of the inherited features are conjugated.

Stereotype.name: ContinuousActivity
Stereotype.notes: The continuous Activity describes the behaviour of a continuous use case.

Stereotype.name: ContinuousUseCase
Stereotype.notes: A continuous use case is a special use case that typically is triggered by a state switch of the system, but could also have an external trigger like the system use case. It has no final result, but continuous results. It's behavior runs continuously and is described by an continuous activity.

Stereotype.name: DomainBlock
Stereotype.notes: A domain block represents an object, a concept, a location, or a person from the real-world domain. A domain block is directly known to the system.

Stereotype.name: Electrical
Stereotype.notes: Model elements with this stereotype are completely allocated to the electrical engineering discipline.

Stereotype.name: EnvironmentalEffect
Stereotype.notes: Represents an relevant effect from the environment on the system, e.g. temperature.

Stereotype.name: ExDeriveReqt
Stereotype.notes: The stereotype adds a property to specify the elements of the model that leads to the derived requirement.

Stereotype.name: ExtendedRequirement
Stereotype.notes: The extended requirement adds some properties to the requirement element that are typically important. Specific projects should add their own properties.

Stereotype.name: ExtendedStakeholder
Stereotype.notes: The stereotype extends the SysML Stakeholder to add additional properties that are used for the SYSMOD Stakeholder.

Stereotype.name: ExternalSystem
Stereotype.notes: Represents a non-human actor.

Stereotype.name: Mechanical
Stereotype.notes: Model elements with this stereotype are completely allocated to the mechanical engineering discipline.

Stereotype.name: MechanicalSystem
Stereotype.notes: External system that has only mechanical interfaces to the system of interest, for instance the floor.

Stereotype.name: Objective
Stereotype.notes: A objective is an objective of the system. It is a special kind of a requirement that is typically not satisfied but amplified by the system.

Stereotype.name: REQUIRES
Stereotype.notes: A REQUIRES constraint is a constraint relationship between two or more variants. The first variant in the ordered set requires the other variants in a valid variant configuration.

Stereotype.name: Sensor
Stereotype.notes: External system that provides data from the environment to the system of interest.

Stereotype.name: Software
Stereotype.notes: Model elements with this stereotype are completely allocated to the software engineering discipline.

Stereotype.name: Subsystem
Stereotype.notes: Subsystem is used for a layer in a system hierarchy (System -> Subsystems -> Blocks).

Stereotype.name: System
Stereotype.notes: Marks the system under development. Typically there is only one block in the model with that stereotype. However in a System of Systems (SoS) model there could be more.

Stereotype.name: SystemContext
Stereotype.notes: A system context is a wrapper around the system and it's actors to allow a detailed system context modeling. The system context references the appropriate system. This is important in a SoS model.

Stereotype.name: SystemProcess
Stereotype.notes: The system process relates use cases that have logical relationships, e.g. an order. The use cases are included and the relationship is modeled with activities or state machines.

Stereotype.name: SystemUseCase
Stereotype.notes: A system use case adds some important properties to the use case element: pre- and postcondition, the signal that triggers the use case, the external result of the use case and the essential flow description.

Stereotype.name: UserInterface
Stereotype.notes: The user interface contains operations that describe the communication with a (human) user. The stereotype emphasizes the special character of the interface in relation to more technical interfaces.

Stereotype.name: UserSystem
Stereotype.notes: External system that is an interface between a human and the system of interest.

Stereotype.name: Variant
Stereotype.notes: A variant is a package that contains all elements of a specific variant of a variation aspect.

Stereotype.name: VariantConfiguration
Stereotype.notes: The variant configuration specifies a valid set of variants.

Stereotype.name: Variation
Stereotype.notes: A Variation package contains all variants of the variation aspect. The tagged values minVariants and maxVariants define the range how many variants of the variation could be configured at the same time.

Stereotype.name: VariationPoint
Stereotype.notes: A Variation point marks an element in the core model. The tagged values reference the variation aspects and the binding time of the variation. The order of variation aspects is conform to the order of the binding time tagged value.

Stereotype.name: WeightedAllocate
Stereotype.notes: The allocate relationship does not express whether the source element is completely or partly allocated to the target element. The stereotype adds a property to give the rate of coverage.

Stereotype.name: WeightedSatisfy
Stereotype.notes: The satisfy relationship does not express whether the source element satisfies the target requirement completely or partly. The stereotype adds a property to give the rate of coverage.

Stereotype.name: WeightedVerify
Stereotype.notes: The verify relationship does not express whether the source element verifies the target requirement completely or partly. The stereotype adds a property to give the rate of coverage.

Stereotype.name: XOR
Stereotype.notes: A XOR constraint is a constraint relationship between two or more variants. Only one of these variants could be part of a variant configuration.
